"@type": "sc:Canvas",
"label": "R24: Federico Barocci, <i>Sketch for 'The Madonna of the Cat' ('La Madonna del Gatto')</i>, before 1575–6, pen and ink, wash and red and black chalk on white paper, (21.7 x 10.7 cm), (inv. 1412 E recto, Gabinetto dei Disegni e delle Stampe degli Uffizi, Florence) <br/>In this ‘primo pensiero’ (first thought) Barocci is pursuing the idea, inspired by the works of Raphael, of placing the two embracing cousins, Saint John the Baptist and Christ, on the Virgin’s lap. However, it is interesting to note that he has not yet thought of introducing the central theme of the painting: the cat chasing the goldfinch, which will distinguish this composition from the traditional Holy Family iconography. As a result, scholars think that this sketch is one of the first surviving preparatory drawings for ‘The Madonna of the Cat (‘La Madonna del Gatto’)’. <br/>© Photo Scala, Florence - courtesy of the Ministero per i Beni e le Attività Culturali\nFile:R-0024-00-000002-PYR.tif (3660x1819px)",
