"@type": "sc:Canvas",
"label": "R28: Federico Barocci, <i>Study for the Virgin and Child with Saint John</i>, before 1575–6, red chalk and pen and ink on white paper, (16.2 x 11 cm), (inv. 1419 E recto, Gabinetto dei Disegni e delle Stampe, Galleria degli Uffizi, Florence) <br/>Of all the surviving preliminary sketches for ‘The Madonna of the Cat (‘La Madonna del Gatto’)’ this is the first one in which the cat makes its appearance. On the top right part of the drawing Barocci explores the group of the Virgin, Christ Child and Saint John the Baptist once more. This time the figures are placed on three different levels: the Virgin in the background, her vivacious son in the middle and his cousin, with his half-extended left leg, in the foreground. With its front paws leaning on the child’s knee, the cat is depicted staring at what appear to be the first indications of a goldfinch in Saint John’s hand. <br/>© By courtesy of the Ministero per i Beni e le Attività Culturali\nFile:R-0028-00-000002-PYR.tif (3894x2728px)",
